  <section xml:id="SECTIONgraph-without-form">
    <title>Graphing Without Formulas</title>

    <p>
      At it<rsq/>s most fundamental a function is just a rule for
      associating a given input with its unique output. For example, we
      could specify a particular function by writing <q>take two copies of the
      input, multiply them together and return the result as output.</q>  This
      is a complete and valid description but it is cumbersome to use.  This
      is why we<rsq/>ve  invented notation that allows us to write
      the description succinctly as the formula <m>f(x)=x^2</m>. It is easy
      to sketch an accurate graph of a function that is given as a formula,
      especially using modern technology, because the formula tells you the
      steps for finding the output for any given input.
    </p>
    <p>

      As mentioned earlier, formulas are the Holy Grail of modern science
      and business.  But, despite what you have seen in your mathematics
      education so far, very often we don<rsq/>t have such a formula. This is the
      usual situation. If you own a trout fishery business for example, you
      would love to have a formula that tells you how many trout your
      fishery will have on any given day of the year. With such a formula
      you could make plans for your business well into the future.  We will
      talk about this in more detail in the next section.
    </p>

    <example  xml:id="EXAMPLEGraphWOFormula">
      <p>
        For example, suppose we have the following information about a
        certain function.  Can we sketch a reasonable graph of the function?
        <ul cols="3">
          <li> <m>y(1)=2 </m></li>
          <li>       <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{1}=0</m></li>
          <li>                 <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{5}=0</m></li>
          <li>     <m>\eval{\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}}{x=3}{}=0</m></li>
          <li>     <m>\eval{\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}}{x=5}{}=0</m></li>
          <li> <p>    <m>\dfdx{y}{x}\gt0</m></p>
          <p>      for all <m>x\lt1</m></p>
          </li>
          <li>          <p> <m> \dfdx{y}{x}\lt0</m></p>
          <p>      for <m>1\lt x\lt 5</m></p>
          <p> and <m>x\gt5</m></p>
          </li>
          <li><p>     <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\gt0</m></p>
          <p>      for <m>3\lt x\lt5</m></p>
          </li>
          <li> <p>    <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt0</m></p>
          <p>      for <m>x\lt3</m></p>
          <p>      and <m>x\gt5</m></p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        
        In a sense this is easier than the previous problems, since intervals
        of increase, decrease, concave up, and concave down have already been
        determined for us.  For example, here are the tables for each.

      </p>
      <table  xml:id="TABLEFDerivTest">
        <title>POTPs</title>

        <tabular>

          <row halign="center" bottom="major">
            <cell>Interval</cell>
            <cell><m>(-\infty, 1)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(1,5)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(5,\infty )</m></cell>
          </row>

          <row halign="center">
            <cell><m>\dfdx{y}{x} </m></cell>
            <cell><m>\dfdx{y}{x}\gt0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\dfdx{y}{x}\lt0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\dfdx{y}{x}\lt0</m></cell>
          </row>

          <row halign="center">
            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\nearrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\searrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\searrow</m></cell>
          </row>


        </tabular>
      </table>


      <table  xml:id="TABLESDerivTest">
        <title>PITPs</title>

        <tabular>

          <row halign="center" bottom="major">
            <cell>Interval</cell>
            <cell><m>(-\infty, 3)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(3,5)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(5,\infty )</m></cell>
          </row>

          <row halign="center">
            <cell><m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2} </m></cell>
            <cell><m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\gt0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt0</m></cell>
          </row>

          <row halign="center">
            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\bigcap</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\bigcup</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\bigcap</m></cell>
          </row>


        </tabular>
      </table>
      
    </example>
    <problem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="EXAMPLEGraphWOFormula"></xref> we have <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{5}=0</m> and
          <m>\dfdx{y}{x}\lt 0</m> on the intervals <m>(1,5)</m> and
          <m>(5,\infty)</m>. Given that <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{5}=0</m> and
          <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt 0</m> when <m>x\gt 5</m>, did we really need to specify
          that <m>\dfdx{y}{x}\lt0</m> on the interval <m>(5,\infty)</m>?


        </p>
      </statement>
    </problem>
    <p>

      Based on the information given, the function <m>y=y(x)</m> has a local
      maximum at <m>x=1</m> and inflection points at <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=5.</m> A sketch
      of the graph might look something  like  this: 
    </p>
    <image source="DC/Optimization6.png" width="90%" />

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Sketch the graph of <m>y=y(x)</m> which satisfies the given requirements.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ul cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>y(-8)=10</m>,
              </li>
              <li><m> \dfdx{y}{x}\lt0</m> for all <m>x</m></li>
              <li> <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\gt0</m></li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ul cols="2">
              <li> <m>y(0)=0</m>,</li>
              <li>         <m>\eval{\dfdx{y}{x}}{x}{0}=0</m>,</li>
