            <p>
              Based on parts (a) and (b) guess what the solution of the IVP
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(-1)=-2</m> will be. Confirm that your guess is
              correct. {If you guess wrong, guess again.}
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Based on parts (a) and (b), and (c) make a conjecture what the solution of the IVP
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(a)=b</m> will be. Confirm that your guess is
              correct.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
</exercise>

      <p>
        <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>slope field</h></idx>
        To sketch the graph of the solution of a given  IVP  begin by
        drawing  the <term>slope field</term> for the differential equation. Then
        plot the  value and follow the slope field to sketch the graph.
      </p>

      <exercise>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>slope field</h></idx>
            For each of the following IVPs sketch the <term>slope field</term> in the
            ranges given and use your slope field to sketch the solution of the
            IVP.
          </p>
          <aside>
            <title>Advice</title>
            <p>
              It is simplest to begin by sketching slopes at integer coordinate
              points and then to fill in between them to get a clearer sense of
              the graphs.}
            </p>
          </aside>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\sqrt{y}</m>,
              <m>y(0)=1</m>,
              <m>-5\le t</m>,
              <m>y\ge0</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y^2</m>,
              <m>y(-1)=-2</m>,
              <m>-5\le t\le 5</m>,
              <m>-5\le y\le 5</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=(y-1)^2</m>,
              <m>y(1)=0</m>,
              <m>-5\le t\le 5</m>,
              <m>-5\le y\le 5</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y(y-2)</m>,
              <m>y(1)=1</m>,
              <m>-1\le x\le 1</m>,
              <m>-2\le y\le 3</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y(2-y)</m>,
              <m>y(1)=1</m>,
              <m>-1\le t\le 1</m>,
              <m>-2\le y\le 3</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=(y^2-1)</m>,
              <m>y(0)=1</m>,
              <m>-2\le t\le 2</m>,
              <m>-2\le y\le 2</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
</exercise>

    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs xml:id="PARAGRAPHSDfdxDependsOnYAndt">
      <title>When  <m>\dfdx{y}{t}</m> Depends on <m>y</m> and <m>t</m></title>

      <p>
        So far we<rsq/>ve examined the situation when <m>\dfdx{y}{t}</m> depends on <m>t</m>
        alone: <me>\dfdx{y}{t}=f(t)</me> and when <m>\dfdx{y}{t}</m> depends on <m>y</m> alone:
        <me>\dfdx{y}{t}=f(y)</me>. But, of course, it could happen at <m>\dfdx{y}{t}</m>
        depends on both <m>y</m> and <m>t</m>:<me>\dfdx{y}{t}=f(t,y)</me>. Analytically, this
        is a more complex situation. However it is possible, and quite useful,
        to get a qualitative sketch of the solution of an IVP from the slope
        field.
      </p>
      <exercise>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>slope field</h></idx>
            For each of the following IVPs draw The <term>slope field</term> in the
            ranges given and use your slope field to sketch the solution of the
            IVP.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=yt</m>,
              <m>y(0)=1</m>,
              <m>-3\le t\le 3</m>,
              <m>y\ge0</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\frac{y}{t^2+1}</m>,
              <m>y(1)=0</m>,
              <m>-5\le x\le 5</m>,
              <m>-5\le y\le 5</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=ye^x</m>,
              <m>y(-4)=2</m>,
              <m>-5\le t\le 5</m>,
              <m>-5\le y\le 5</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=ye^{-x}</m>,
              <m>y(0)=2</m>,
              <m>0\le t\le 5</m>,
              <m>-5\le y\le 5</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
</exercise>

    </paragraphs>
    

